export const CODEBOOK_SECTION = "CODEBOOK (apply triggers strictly — extracted from master.xlsx; do not infer beyond what is stated here)\n\nDIMENSION SCORING\n\nD1 — INSTITUTIONAL ABSORPTION LOAD\n- 1 (Low): Single lead implementing agency; no inter-ministerial coordination required; project sits within existing mandate of one body; no new coordination units needed\n  Decision rule: All implementation decisions can be made by one agency without external sign-off\n- 2 (Moderate): 2–3 agencies involved; at least one new coordination mechanism (joint committee, inter-agency MoU, or working group) required; at least one agency needs new internal units or procedures\n  Decision rule: Project requires a steering committee with multi-agency representation OR requires one agency to formally delegate authority to another\n- 3 (High): 4+ agencies and/or ministries involved; requires a new permanent inter-institutional body; project crosses two or more policy domains (e.g. finance + forestry + justice); implementing agency has documented capacity gaps in the project area\n  Decision rule: Score 3 if: (a) the project's own action document lists 4+ named counterpart institutions, OR (b) a mid-term evaluation or audit has flagged coordination failure as a risk, OR (c) the government underwent a ministerial reshuffle during implementation\n\nD2 — REGULATORY DEPENDENCIES\n- 1 (Low): Project operates entirely within existing legal framework; at most requires internal procedural updates (circulars, ministerial resolutions); no new legislation or secondary regulation needed\n  Decision rule: Legal basis for all core activities already exists in current law\n- 2 (Moderate): Requires new secondary legislation (reglamentos, decrees, ministerial regulations) or significant updates to existing regulations; primary legal framework exists but has material gaps; regulatory updates can be done by executive action without parliament\n  Decision rule: At least one specific regulatory gap is identified in the project's action document or risk matrix\n- 3 (High): Requires new primary legislation (congressional approval); requires overhaul of existing legal framework; requires ratification of international agreements; or regulatory gap is so fundamental it blocks implementation until resolved\n  Decision rule: Score 3 if: (a) the project explicitly lists pending legislation as a precondition, OR (b) the project requires a new national system (e.g. SALH) that has no legal basis in current forestry law, OR (c) implementation requires constitutional-level changes\n\nD3 — TECHNICAL DEPENDENCIES\n- 1 (Low): Project is technically self-contained; deploys on existing national IT infrastructure; requires no integration with external systems; primary output is human capacity or procedural change\n  Decision rule: No new platforms, data centres, or APIs required; existing systems sufficient\n- 2 (Moderate): Requires integration with 1–2 existing core national systems (e.g. civil registry, customs single window, payment gateway); may require API development or data exchange protocols; builds on existing infrastructure with moderate upgrades\n  Decision rule: Score 2 if the project requires connecting to national backbone systems but does not require building new backbone infrastructure\n- 3 (High): Requires building new national-level IT infrastructure from scratch; requires integration with 3+ systems simultaneously; requires cross-border interoperability layer; depends on systems that do not yet exist; requires proprietary hardware deployment at scale\n  Decision rule: Score 3 if: (a) the action document specifies development of a new national IT system, OR (b) integration requires connecting to both domestic and international platforms simultaneously, OR (c) the project's technical output is a prerequisite for another project's technical layer\n\nD4 — POLITICAL SENSITIVITY\n- 1 (Low): Technocratic in nature; no identifiable vested interests threatened; cross-party consensus likely; implementation agency is insulated from electoral cycles; no significant civil society opposition\n  Decision rule: Score 1 if no vested interest is threatened AND no Score 2 or 3 trigger is met. (Trade facilitation, technical standards, and connectivity projects are typical examples, not an automatic rule.)\n- 2 (Moderate): Some identifiable stakeholders who lose relative advantage; moderate media visibility; project intersects with one politically sensitive policy area (e.g. land tenure, public sector reform); implementation could be slowed but not blocked by political change\n  Decision rule: Score 2 if the project's action document identifies political will as a risk factor but assesses it as manageable\n- 3 (High): Directly threatens entrenched economic or political interests; country CPI below 35/100 (Transparency International) AND project involves anti-corruption tools, public finance transparency, or resource governance; project has been subject to documented political interference; implementation agency changed or abolished after election\n  Decision rule: Score 3 if: (a) CPI < 35 AND project domain is transparency/governance, OR (b) action document rates political risk as High, OR (c) there is documented evidence of government resistance (e.g. amnesties for officials, ministerial obstruction)\n\nD5 — INVESTMENT NEEDS & FUNDING\n- 1 (Low): Funding secure: financing agreement signed AND funding gap ≤ 10% of total declared budget\n  Decision rule: Confirmed funding ≥ 90% of total. 'Confirmed' = signed financing agreement, adopted EU AAP allocation, MDB board-approved amount, or signed bilateral commitment letter. Budget SIZE is recorded in the Lead Donor/Funder column and does NOT affect the score.\n- 2 (Moderate): Funding partly secured: at least one tranche's agreement signed AND funding gap 10–30% of total\n  Decision rule: Confirmed funding 70–90% of total; remaining tranches in confirmed pipeline (board approval / AAP adoption / signed commitment letter). Amounts labelled indicative, planned, or expected do NOT count as confirmed.\n- 3 (High): Funding at risk: funding gap > 30% of total; OR no financing agreement signed (under preparation); OR blended finance dependent on private co-financing not yet committed\n  Decision rule: Confirmed funding < 70% of total. funding gap = (total declared budget − confirmed funding) ÷ total declared budget. Total declared budget includes announced future tranches within the current programming cycle, but excludes scale-up explicitly described as separate future funding rounds.\n\nINTERACTION TYPES (cite the trigger that fired in interaction_note)\n- Complementary — Projects address different components of the same outcome; parallel execution is beneficial and each project strengthens the other's impact\n  Trigger: Score this when: projects share a beneficiary group or policy objective but have distinct implementing agencies and non-overlapping technical outputs\n- Sequentially Dependent — Project B cannot achieve its objectives unless Project A has reached a specified milestone first; parallel execution wastes resources or creates system conflicts\n  Trigger: Score this when: Project B's technical input is Project A's output, OR Project B's implementing agency depends on capacity built by Project A\n- Institutionally Competing — Both projects draw on the same implementing agency or the same pool of senior counterpart officials simultaneously, creating overload risk\n  Trigger: Score this when: both projects list the same lead agency AND combined Institutional Load scores sum to 5 or above within a single country\n- Governance-Conflicting — Projects create contradictory rules, parallel systems for the same function, overlapping mandates, or misaligned incentive structures\n  Trigger: Score this when: two projects create separate digital systems for the same data type (e.g. two timber tracking systems), OR two projects assign the same regulatory function to different agencies\n\nOVERALL RISK LEVEL (derive overall_risk strictly from these rules)\n- L (Low): Composite 5–7. Complementary only; no Sequentially Dependent or Governance-Conflicting links. Action: Monitor at annual review; no structural intervention needed.\n- M (Medium): Composite 8–10. Any Institutionally Competing interaction; OR Sequentially Dependent below the High threshold; OR Complementary with composite 8–15. Action: Phased implementation recommended; coordination mechanism required before T3 investment.\n- H (High): Composite 11–15. Any Governance-Conflicting interaction; OR Sequentially Dependent with composite ≥ 11 or predecessor incomplete / disbursement < 20%; OR Political Sensitivity = 3 AND Technical Dependencies = 3 on the same project. Action: Parallel implementation not advisable; sequencing intervention required; donor coordination meeting recommended before next funding commitment.";
